ser and one winner will later speak.</p><p>At Camp Obama, Suzanne Malveaux is shouting into a microphone that they've basically had to stick right inside her mouth to be heard.  The last two times they cut to her, they couldn't hear a single word.  This time we can hear, at least, the kind of words you can always hear when people have those rock-star microphones, you can hear someone shouting '<em>FUZZ YOFFLE JZUJZ AN OBAMA SCHZH!</em>\" like they're trying to land a fighter plane. The people in Grant Park behind her are yelling and excited. Very VERY excited.</p><p>Dana Bash is in a ballroom in Phoenix, where a the Phoenix Boy's choir is singing a quiet, mournful number while people stand around and sip wine in a  totally plumberesque, unelitist fashion.  What's the mood there, she's asked by Wolf Blitzer?  Oh, quiet, she says.  Realistic. Stoic. </p><p>Stoic. Interesting word.</p><!-- Block 11 --><p><strong>8:42pm:</strong> On Fox, the state is called by a graphic of the faces of McCain and Obama flipping on individual cards like that Victorian optical illusion with a bird on one side and a cage on the other where a spinning thread puts the bird inside the cage.  There is therefore a lot more that could be done with this graphic. McCain on one side of the spinning graphic, a beautiful bouncing baby on the other: spin the graphic, McCain kisses the baby.  Obama on one side of the spinning card, Bill Ayers on the other, spin the card, 'Bama cavorts with terrorists!  Come ON, Fox, you just weren't working hard enough with those now, were you.</p><p>Meanwhile, they're showing the massive swell of supporters who have turned up to Grant Park in hope of seeing a new president speak later on. \"That's a great turn out\" the anchor and correspondent agree. \"Barack Obama; lucky with the weather. AGAIN.\"</p><p>Yes. That's why those people are there. It's not raining.</p><p>Anyone curious about the BBC toupee question, meanwhile, can enter the debate on a more informed level by looking at the screengrab someone's helpfully uploaded for me <a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/mrbiggs/3003525421/\">here</a>.  I say it IS.  What do you say?</p><!-- Block 12 --><p><strong>9:18pm:</strong> If I'm informed one more time on one more channel that 270 is a magic number, I may take 270 pencils, and stick one up a single nostril on 270 news anchors. </p><p>At the moment, as the polls close but remain too close to call and the map fills up with 'Dunno Yet Yellow', the battle of the touchscreen against the CGI is on.  On CNN, voter analysis with crazy hands on a touch-sensitive whiteboard reveals things that people either knew already or can't analyse  - apparently 52% of people said that race was a motivating factor and, in a seperate question, 53% race made no difference to their vote at all.  </p><p>MSNBC, meanwhile, presents the staes so far from entirely within a virtual sentate.  Virtual columns and a virtual whiteboard (that's almost exactly the same size and shape as CNN's REAL whiteboard, but weirdly higher-tech because it's completely non-physical) surround the man who stands by a real podium  - one real laptop in front of him - pointing at the whiteboard behind him that isn't there.</p><p>And yet none of them is saying anything wildly different.  And most of them, with great anticipation and breathless portent, are barely saying anything at all.</p><!-- Block 13 --><p><strong>9:35pm:</strong> Katie Couric - and I can't believe we've neglected her so far, apologies to all her fans - is being more strident on CBS than anyone I've so far seen. \"Obama's on 190 votes, on his way to 270\" (270? Really? Is that an important number, then?) \"and the presidency; John  McCain's running out of ways to win.  This is election night in USA\"  she says, sounding a little bit like she's called it already.</p><p>She also has great hair.</p><p>ABC's on the streets of New York, amid the crowds in Times square, shouting happy shouts to keep themselves warm. At least I <em>think</em> that's why they're doing it, unless they've secretly been listening to Katie Couric.</p><!-- Block 14 --><p><strong>9:48pm:</strong> You know what's an important number, as well as 270?  3.  Three is, as De La Soul once said, a magic number.  Because the channels don't want to call things until they feel completely sure ...  but then most of them seem to feel sure enough to call it once 3% of precincts in any particular state have declared.</p><p>On ABC, they're going further than Times Square.  Correspondent for the Continent of Africa (I think that's her official title) Dana is in Kenya, in Kogelo, in fact, the ancestral home of the Obama family.  </p><p>We're told, before we speak to her, that the world's press have descended on this tiny, rural community, and we can see the towns people gathered behind Dana on plastic chairs wearing colourful baseball caps, faces lit by something just off screen.</p><p>Before we cut to Dana (by live satellite link), the studio has a question: \"Just how accurate are the results they're getting there?  Are they getting results at all yet? Are they at all up to date?\"</p><p>And how are they getting those?  Is it by smoke signal? Or by carrier pigeon?  Or perhaps - call me crazy - by Live Satellite Link?</p><p>Sadly Dana cannot hear us, ABC's feed keeps cutting out.</p><p>\"In this tiny village, where there are usually only less than 500 people, there is actually a LARGE SCREEN where they are actually watching INTERNATIONAL TELEVISION and the results are actually coming in, as quickly as they are over there, and they're actually CHEERING as the results come in from each state!\"</p><p>Are they?  Actually? In AFRICA? Madness!<br/>Well, they can't be watching it on ABC, then, their feed is shonky. They're probably tuned to the CNN - or someone else with the 3% rule.</p><!-- Block 15 --><p><strong>9:56pm:</strong> \"We're going to take a break, while we eat cookies, and then we'll be right back\"</p><p>CNN may have holograms, ABC definitely has a Correspondent  for the Continent of Africa: Fox has biscuits someone's brought in, decorated to look like a high-def widescreen TV tuned immovably to Fox News.</p><p>I can't help but wonder if, as I flick through the channels, I'm always <em>just</em> missing the really awesome technological advances in television graphics.</p><!-- Block 16 --><p><strong>10.05pm:</strong> Ok, it's 10pm on the East Coast, Silly AM in the UK and almost Pizza O'Clock at my house, and on twitter I'm seeing lots of people calling it already.  Iowa for Obama, they say, and with California and other big blue states yet to be called, the internet is starting to buzz with early calls.</p><p>\"Every time they call it for Barack, we take a shot\" says <a href=\"http://twitter.com/TinaFey/status/990699933\">Tina Fey on Twitter</a>.  I like the woman's style, but I hope someone else is driving her home, because she's going to be HAMMERED in a minute.</p><!-- Block 17 --><p><strong>10:39pm:</strong> It's remarkable when you flick over and see the local channels who don't have the big network billions to throw at fancy graphics.  It feels like you're travelling back in time, like suddenly they'll cut to the weather and someone will start placing large magnetic clouds on gaudy-coloured maps. These flat 2D images of a giant USA, states coloured a stark RED or a BLUE with no sense of sensitive aesthetic judgement involved. </p><p>Hell, on ABC the maps may be flat but they're shaded, county by county throughout the state, redder where the vote is stronger, fading to a  gentle pastel pink blush where the Rebulicans won but only barely.  It's a mottled, marbled view of the major election on a macro scale, and as the analysts take their magic pens and scrawl illustrative circles and arrows and marks on the screen, it somewhat feels like someone's taking a felt tip to a Georges Seurat painting.</p><p>Well, kinda.</p><p>Anyway, as they're moving through, rushing from delicately shaded red state to delicately blushing blue one, it means very little at all - would be great if you could stop and look in depth, but there is not time, for depth, just impressive graphics, my friends. So it basically, at this speed, means feck-all.</p><p>Looks purdy, though.</p><!-- Block 18 --><p><strong>10:49pm:</strong> I'd be doing some more channel-flicking if I hadn't got rather stuck staring at Katie Couric.  She really is remarkable.  Looking, I mean.  There's just something ethereal about her.  And I'm trying to decide what that is, so I'm having to watch correspondent after correspondent in split screen interviews until I can see someone next to her in real life to decide.</p><p>Because if she's always in soft focus, that's one thing, and all very well. So then whoever sat next to her would also be in soft focus, and we would know.</p><p>But it's almost more than that.  It's almost as if she looks like she's <strong>always</strong> in soft focus. So if you met her in person, you'd just be overwhelmed by the fact her features are all slightly blurred.  <br/>Perhaps she has a soft downy fur covering her that diffuses the light from the cameras?<br/>Or perhaps, like a beautiful pumpkin lantern, she has some kind of softly flickering internal light source?<br/>Or maybe she releases a fine mist of steam into the air around her, to create a more flattering focus for her face at any angle they might catch?</p><p>Whatever it is, it's remarkable. Please, let's drink to Katie Couric.</p><p>Or, perhaps, to Obama.  Who, from the returns starting to dribble in ever faster, seems to be pulling off a pretty crushing win.  The people in Grant Park in Chicago seem to be feeling it, though.  A million of them, standing and waiting.  A million?  Really? Wow.</p><!-- Block 19 --><p><strong>10:56pm:</strong> The internet is buzzing with the rumour that all the networks will call it officially at 11pm ET. That's four minutes from now.</p><p>I'm excitedly waiting, and desperately trying to decide quickly which channel to watch it on.  They're all much of a muchness, but Fox may be sweetest, I suppose...</p><!-- Block 20 --><p><strong>11:02pm:</strong> AND THEY'VE CALLED IT.  </p><p>Every single network, has it on big screens BARACK OBAMA ELECTED PRESIDENT.</p><p>CNN with shots of a cheering Grant Park, Fox with glasses tipped to the end of the nose and a mournful face. MSNBC has college students cheering and children jumping up and down in Times Square, on ANC the noise is deafening.</p><p>This is, frankly, a very exciting thing to watch.</p><!-- Block 21 --><p><strong>11:13pm:</strong> \"There's always celebration on one side or the other\" says ABC, with great analytical flair \"but I've never seen anything like this\"</p><p>On CNN, they're quoting from Martin Luth King Jr and from the constitution.</p><p>On Fox they're talking about Bill Ayers ... but then moving on to say what a promising figure Obama is and how they've thought so all along.</p><p>MSNBC are doing a marathon voiceover over crowds of cheering people in Grant Park (\"<em> ... And the remarkable thing about the fact that the analysis will prove that the crowds came out in numbers like were never before imagined when they thought about what kind of numbers might possibly be imaginable at such a time and in such an occasion when ...</em>\" Oh, God Bless rolling news)</p><p>And on the comedy network Stephen Colbert has a parrot on his shoulder.</p><!-- Block 22 --><p><strong>11:24pm:</strong> The camera has been lingering on The Reverend Jesse Jackson having a cry in the crowd at grant park for around four minutes now.</p><p>In fact, the only thing that could possibly make them cut away, makes them cut: </p><p><strong>A concession speech by John McCain.</strong></p><p>\"A few minutes ago, I had the honour of calling Senator Obama ...\"</p><p><em>BOOOOO, BOOOOOO!</em> says the crowd, quietened only slightly by the soft padding hands of John McCain.</p><p>\"