 going to miss crawling into work in the early hours of the weekend mornings, sharing the streets with stragglers from the London booze and drug scene, to find handball on the telly and a bunch of weirdos in my inbox.</p><p>But please stay with me for one more day, weirdos. It's a pretty light morning on competition in Beijing, so we're going to need some of your emails. Before you get too excited, I'm not fielding anything about the GB/Autralia non-competition. Aussies: you got fewer medals (gold and total) than the Brits and I don't care how sizeable your population relative to Britain's. And Brits, let's just let it lie already, OK. By all means take to the streets of Brisbane with your gloating, but leave it out here, all right.</p><p>So, in the absence of that, what have we left? Well, there's the <strong>American basketball team</strong> on the court in the gold medal match: they're 22-22 against Spain in the first quarter as I type. I know some of the Americans -- <strong>Kobe</strong>, <strong>LeBron</strong>, <strong>Carmelo</strong>, they're all my bros; I know none of the Spanish, and for this reason I'm supporting the NBA divas and the wannabes.</p><p>Later on, there's the <strong>closing ceremony</strong> and the main event - Britain's 10-minute presentation as the Olympic mantle officially transfers to London. That's going to be a spectacular shambles and I can't wait. I fully expect it'll only be necessary to describe in the plainest of terms what's happening on the screen and it'll be a comedy masterpiece; no embellishment necessary.</p><p>That won't be for another few hours yet, so back to the basketball. It's 33-27 to USA.</p><!-- Block 50 --><p><strong>7.37am: </strong> The <strong>men's basketball gold medal match</strong> has just tipped-off. So there's no better time to hand you over to Howard Swains. Wow, that's it from me. See you in four years.</p><!-- Block 49 --><p><strong>7.28am: </strong>All those clips below are from past Olympics. So here are my top-five (admittedly Brit-focused) moments from Beijing 2008. In no particular order:</p><p>1) <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/aug/17/olympics2008.rowing\">GB's women's quadruple sculls are beaten into second place</a>, cue a John Inverdale interview with tears and wry smiles.<br/>2) Christine Ohuruogu looks down and out after the first half of the women's 400m. <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/aug/19/christineohuruogu.olympicsathletics\">But Sanya Richards tires, and the rest, as they say, is history</a>.<br/>3) Sport and politics are always destined to mix. So with conflict between the two countries raging, Russia took on Georgia (well two Brazilians really) in the women's beach volleyball. <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/aug/13/olympics2008.olympicsvolleyball?gusrc=rss&amp;feed=sport\">And Georgia came out on top</a>.<br/>4) On paper it sounds boring, but the 10km swim is actually quite compelling. David Davies seemed to have it all wrapped up, but then he started swimming in the wrong direction. Eventually cancer survivor Maarten van der Weijden came through to take gold, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/aug/21/swimming.britisholympicteam\">but Davies fought delirium to hang on for silver</a>.<br/>5) I suppose it's a tie between <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/aug/17/olympics2008.olympicsaquatics\">Michael Phelps' remarkable achievement</a> and <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/aug/17/olympicsathletics.olympics2008\">Usain Bolt's</a> startling brilliance. Both utterly amazing, in their own separate way.<br/>Agree, disagree? Let me know.</p><!-- Block 48 --><p><strong>7.09am: </strong>It's all over. I told you...GOLD FOR USA. Stanley is the man. What a final, way better than the football yesterday.</p><!-- Block 47 --><p><strong>7.07am: </strong>One match point saved by Brazil.</p><!-- Block 46 --><p><strong>7.06am: </strong>This volleyball malarkey isn't half bad. USA are on the verge of a shock victory. Brazil have gone to pieces.</p><!-- Block 45 --><figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_zi0_LjHHN4\">  <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"385\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/_zi0_LjHHN4?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen>  </iframe></figure><p><strong>6.58am: </strong>Actually, this is it. I mentioned it earlier, and it is well-known, but it always sets my bottom lip aquiver.</p><!-- Block 44 --><figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pqi2bT_TqDs\">  <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"385\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Pqi2bT_TqDs?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen>  </iframe></figure><p><strong>6.51am: </strong>Permit me some self-indulgence readers. Above is one of my favourite Olympic moments. What are yours?</p><!-- Block 43 --><p><strong>6.47am: </strong> The basketball bronze medal match is over, and argentina have the bronze. They beat Lithuania 87-75.</p><!-- Block 42 --><p><strong>6.44am: </strong>China have won another medal, Zou Shiming has claimed gold in the light-flyweight boxing.</p><!-- Block 41 --><p><strong>6.40am: </strong> If you're not as gripped with the volleyball as I am, Spain are taking on Croatia for the <strong>handball bronze medal</strong>. Plus there are a host of boxing finals going on, if you want some fist-flailing action.</p><!-- Block 40 --><p><strong>6.35am: </strong><strong>Volleyball </strong>Tactically the USA are playing this just right. They've now gone 2-1 up against the much fancied Brazilians.</p><!-- Block 39 --><p><strong>6.10am: </strong>Jeanne Perrett wants to know what time the closing ceremony starts. Well Jeanne, I'm here to serve. The festivities kick-off at 1300 BST or 2000 Beijing time. Apparently you can look forward to three hours of \"action\".</p><!-- Block 38 --><p><strong>6.08am: </strong>U...S...A...U...S...A...U...S...A...U...S...A...U...S...A, My boys have leveled things up; it's one set apiece in the <strong>volleyball.</strong></p><!-- Block 37 --><p><strong>6.05am: </strong>Over on the <strong>basketball</strong> court Argentina are currently beating Lithuania 57-39 in the bronze medal match. hopefully it's whetting your appetite for the main course of the USA v Spain.</p><!-- Block 36 --><p><strong>5.58am: </strong>I make no apologies for missing the result of the rhythmic gymnastics all-around group competition. Apparently Russia took gold with a totally arbitrary score of 35.550. China were second and Belarus took the bronze. I, for one, can't wait 'til next time.</p><!-- Block 35 --><p><strong>5.50am: </strong>As i predicted the USA are fighting back in the <strong>volleyball</strong>. They lead 17-14 in the second set.</p><!-- Block 34 --><p><strong>5.28am: </strong>Pommie Barsteward has added to <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/aug/23/olympics20082\">the 100 things that they have learned in Beijing</a>. He proposes two new entries. <br/>101. <a href=\"http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/08/24/2344788.htm?site=olympics/2008\">Aussie gold medals cost the tax payer $16.7m each</a>. <br/><a href=\"http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/08/24/2344844.htm?site=olympics/2008\">102. And Aussies aren't the world's most gracious losers</a>.</p><!-- Block 33 --><p><strong>5.20am: </strong>The Olympics is all about tear jerking tales (watch Derek Redmond hobbling down the finishing straight and I defy you not to blub). Anyway Josh in Cambodia has this to say (I'm not even going to edit it): \"I live in Phnom Penh, Cambodia, a country with 4 Olympians. Their most promising athlete is a marathon runner, Hem Bunting, who got a silver medal in the Asian games last year. Anyway, I don't know how he did today (remarkably tough to find out on the Olympics website), but the guy has no funding, can't afford to buy training shoes, and is sometimes even locked out of the Olympic Stadium in Phnom Penh where he trains. He therefore trains by running around Phnom Penh, breathing diesel fumes and risking death by motorcycle.\" So if there are any representatives from large multinational sports corporations reading this, how about throwing some money his way!?</p><!-- Block 32 --><p><strong>5.17am: </strong><strong>GB&amp;NI news</strong> Chris Hoy has been confirmed as the Great Britain flag bearer for the closing ceremony of the 2008 Olympics.</p><!-- Block 31 --><p><strong>5.10am: </strong>USA player Lloy Ball is a massive Rage Against the Machine fan apparently. He really should have been at Reading Festival on Friday instead of galavanting  around at the Olympics.</p><!-- Block 30 --><p><strong>5.02am: </strong>Finally I've found out why there's one guy on each team with a different coloured shirt. I always assumed it was some kind of fashion statement. But it's because they are the 'libero', the ball control specialist. 4-1 to Brazil by the way</p><!-- Block 29 --><p><strong>4.57am: </strong>Right is everyone rrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrready for the men's gold medal match in the volleyball. It's a heavyweight clash: USA v Brazil. I'm excited. In the style of Two-Face I've flicked a coin and I can reveal that the USA are going to win. U...S...A...U...S...A...U...S...A...U...S...A...U...S...A</p><!-- Block 28 --><p><strong>4.46am: </strong>Oliver Pattenden sheds some light on why people may not be reading: \"Team GB is up for sod all today, so we're saving ourselves for the pageant of Britishness later on.\" <em>I'm cringing already at the thought of all the old clichés being wheeled out. However, it will be nice that Bozza Johnson will be there to show the world that nothing much has changed since GB last held the Olympics in 1948. </em></p><!-- Block 27 --><p><strong>4.32am: </strong><strong>READERS WHERE ARE YOU!?</strong> I need your witty, irreverent banter to help me through these awkward hours of non-sport. It's your last chance. After today I'll be disappearing into the ether never to be seen again.</p><!-- Block 26 --><p><strong>4.30am: </strong>I'm sorry, but I can't get into this rhythmic gymnastics guff. It's like one of those pretentious live art installations - boring, boring, boring. I wish there was some handball on, now that's a sport.</p><!-- Block 25 --><p><strong>4.26am: </strong>They think it's all over...it is now. Russia have claimed the bronze medal in the <strong>men's volleyball</strong>. Beating Italy 3-0.</p><!-- Block 24 --><p><strong>4.25am: </strong>Here's something I don't understand, why are sports like rhythmic gymnastics and synchronised swimming in the Olympics when cricket, golf and rugby not? Absolute nonsense if you ask me, oh and don't get me started on baseball and softball. Plus if you're going to have archery, you've got to allow darts. I'm sure you're all bored by these anglocentric arguments, but I'm getting quite emotional as end draws near.</p><!-- Block 23 --><p>4.20am: Right, where are we. Russia are two sets and 20-18 up over Italy in the <strong>men's bronze medal volleyball match</strong>. And as I promised, over in the Beijing University of Technology Gymnasium, there's some rather delightful choreography going on in the <strong>rhythmic gymnastics</strong>.</p><!-- Block 22 --><p><strong>4.11am: </strong>It's just after 4am, time for some subtle plugging. <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/aug/24/olympics2008.olympicsathletics\">Anna Kessel interviews Usain Bolt</a>, <a href=\"http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/08/24/games_for_all_as_britain_shine.html\">Kevin Mitchell blogs about the Games' unsung heroes</a> and our writers reveal <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2008/aug/23/olympics20082\">the 100 things that they have learned in Beijing</a>.</p><!-- Block 21 --><p><strong>3.45am: </strong> According to Pommie Barsteward in Queensland: \"Kate Ellis, the Aussie sports minister, has been consuming vast quantities of humble pie on Aussie TV this morning. You may recall she had a bet with her UK counterpart before the Games regarding which nation would be placed highest in the medal table and, as she's on the losing end of the wager, she now has to wear a GB-related t-shirt at her next media appearance. Maybe some MBM readers would like to contribute some suitable design suggestions for the aforementioned apparel?\"</p><!-- Block 20 --><p><strong>3.42am: </strong>Shamini in Singapore has not been fully convinced by the Beijing Games: \"There's been too much sanctioned cheating and silly events - but Phelps and even more so Bolt have elevated sport to a new level - Bolt has restored my faith in the pure undiluted brilliance of the human spirit!\"</p><!-- Block 19 --><p><strong>3.35am: </strong> One way traffic in the <strong>volleyball</strong>. Russia are one set up and leading 8-1 in the second.</p><!-- Block 18 --><p><strong>3.18am: </strong> Greg in Margaret River, Australia (which, by the way I've heard is a lovely place) reckons the Guardian's medal table is short changing our cousin over in Oz. Well, I did say we hadn't deliberately altered the USA's total, but I can't be so sure about Australia's. After all us Brits have had to endure years of sporting torment at the hands of the Wallabies. Maybe we'll let you win the Ashes next year to make you feel better.</p><!-- Block 17 --><p><strong>3.10am: </strong>So it appears that the real leader of Great Britain, David Beckham, is going to play a prominent role in the closing ceremony. \"It's going to be very different from the opening ceremony, which was burdened with heavy responsibility to show Chinese culture to the world,\" one of the directors, Miao Pei, told China's Southern Metropolis News.  Mind you I'd rather see Becks over in Beijing playing the diplomat than clogging up England's right side with his one-dimensional punting.</p><!-- Block 16 --><p><strong>3.07am: </strong> Right now that the marathon has been sorted out, there's some <strong>men's volleyball</strong> medals up for grabs. Russia take on Italy in the bronze medal match. It's currently 8-4 to Russia. Can they hang on? I have no idea.</p><!-- Block 15 --><p><strong>2.55am: </strong>Dan Robinson finishes 24th with a time of just over 2 hours 16 minutes. 24th may not sound great, but in the conditions it was a truly monumental effort.</p><!-- Block 14 --><p><strong>2.46am: </strong>Brendon Foster has added some much needed doom and gloom to the proceedings, pointing out that no British male distance runners have finished in the top eight for the first time since 1896. Good one Brendon, there's been way too much unadulterated joy for my liking too.</p><!-- Block 13 --><p><strong>2.44am: </strong>Merga looks absolutely knackered, as team-mate Kebede overtakes him to grab the bronze medal. Fourth place is the cruelest position. London Marathon winner Martin Lel finishes fifth.</p><!-- Block 12 --><p><strong>2.40am: </strong><strong>Marathon </strong>Samuel Wanjiru is greeted by thousands of fans in the Bird's Nest Stadium. He's run a great race, outlasting all the rest. It's GOLD for Kenya in a new Olympic record time. Gharib of Morocco gets the silver.</p><!-- Block 11 --><p><strong>2.35am: </strong>Tony Jarrett (possibly the famous hurdler, who knows) says: \"It has been really great to see so many Union Jacks waved by happy, often triumphant people, without listening to hatred and abuse of other countries.\"</p><!-- Block 10 --><p><strong>2.30am: </strong>Back to the <strong>marathon</strong>. Wanjiru is sweating profusely as he makes a break. The gold medal is now his to lose.</p><!-- Block 9 --><p><strong>2.23am: </strong>Oh dear more 'issues' with the medal table Stephen Vaughn says: \"Could you please explain why the Guardian's medal count shows 103 medals for the United States, rather than the 107 that the U.S. has actually won? Are you docking us 4 medals for George W. Bush?\"<br/><em>I can assure you Stephen that it's not Guardian policy to alter results according to political leanings. Although if Obama was incharge.....</em></p><!-- Block 8 --><p><strong>2.18am: </strong>Having only just got into the office, I'm shocked to see the Russians have leap frogged GB&amp;NI. Well it was good while it lasted.</p><!-- Block 7 --><p><strong>2.10am: </strong>In the <strong>marathon</strong> it looks like we're down to three. Deriba Merga, Samuel Kamau Wanjiru and Jaouad Gharib will duke it out for gold, silver and bronze.</p><!-- Block 6 --><p><strong>2.02am: </strong>Don't you just love how sport gives politicians the opportunity to spout off. Scottish Sports minister Stewart Maxwell says that Scotland should compete in its own right at the 2012 Olympics and not as part of Team GB. \"\"This is an exceptionally brilliant nation - at the same time a small nation. Scotland can compete on the world stage - we proved that in the Olympics - and a Scottish team at the Olympics is the future,\" he said.</p><!-- Block 5 --><p><strong>2.00am: </strong><strong>Marathon </strong> drama. The relentless pace has forced out Luke Kibet. This is all getting a bit ridiculous now, Martin Lel is even struggling.</p><!-- Block 4 --><p><strong>1.55am: </strong>If we're to believe all the hyperbole this has been the greatest Olympics ever. Spitz's medal haul was smashed and Michael Johnson now looks like a Sunday morning jogger when compared to the Lightning Bolt. But has it really been that great? How many times have the hairs on the back of your neck stood up or tears flowed down your face? Let me know.</p><!-- Block 3 --><p><strong>1.50am: </strong>\"But what else is happening?\", I hear you ask. Well on my watch you can look forward to medal matches in <strong>men's basketball</strong>, <strong>men's water polo</strong>, <strong>men's handball</strong> and <strong>men's volleyball</strong>. Plus they'll be some prancing and dancing in the <strong>rhythmic gymnastics</strong>.</p><!-- Block 2 